ed Kingdom","East Newton, Cambridge, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","East Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thornton,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Thornton, Lord of East Newton was born in 1325, in Newton, Yorkshire, England. He married Joan Nellison. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1345, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1325–1345":"1325–1345","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","1319–1344":"1319–1344","1321–Female":"1321–Surnud","1318–1402":"1318–1402","1339–1374":"1339–1374","1341–1402":"1341–1402","1343–Male":"1343–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1291–1333":"1291–1333","1294–1336":"1294–1336","1341":"1341","1374":"1374","1294":"1294","before 1329":"enne 1329","1291":"1291","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1336":"1336","1402":"1402","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1344":"1344","ABT 1343":"umbes 1343","1453":"1453","1343":"1343","1321":"1321","about 1333":"umbes 1333","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Newton, Cambridge, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yo